[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:
   We have to choose an increasing sequence b₁<…<bₙ in [0..m], to maximize 
     ∑₁ⁿ popcount(bᵢ)·aᵢ.
   This is equivalent to matching the weight sequence A=(a₁…aₙ) to a subsequence of length n drawn (in order) from the very long sequence S of popcounts of 0,1,2,…,m.  We must pick n positions in S (indices increasing) to maximize the dot‐product A⋅picked_entries.  
   Category: DP on a binary trie (divide‐&‐conquer DP on the bit‐trie of [0..m]).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:
   We build an implicit binary trie of all numbers 0..m, where at depth d we test bit m_d.  A leaf in this trie corresponds to one number x≤m, and each internal edge “right” contributes +1 to popcount.  
   We do a post‐order DP: for each node u, compute dp_u[k]=maximum sum when picking k leaves from u’s subtree to match A[1..k].  Merging two child DP arrays f (left) and g (right) is a knapsack‐like convolution:

     dp_u[k] = max_{i+j=k} { f[i] + g[j] + sum_{t=i+1..i+j} aₜ },

   since each pick in the right child subtree incurs +1 bit‐count at this level, contributing aₜ.  We precompute prefix sums P so sum_{t=i+1..i+j} aₜ = P[i+j]−P[i].   
   We cap all subtree sizes to ≤n as we cannot pick more than n leaves in total.

3. Complexity Analysis:
   Let L=⎡log₂(m+1)⎤ ≤60.  The trie has O(L) internal nodes.  At each node we merge two DP arrays of lengths up to n, costing O(n²).  Total time O(L·n²) ≈60·200²≈2.4·10⁶ ops, easily within contest limits.  
   Space is O(n·L) for recursion and DP arrays; with n=200, L≈60 that's modest.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:
   • m may be just below a power of two—handle the “prefixLess” flag carefully to know when a subtree is full vs. limited by m.  
   • aᵢ can be negative—prefix sums P and DP must allow negative values.  
   • Cap all dp‐vector sizes to min(subtree_size,n)+1 to avoid needless work.  
   • Use a sufficiently negative “–INF” for impossible states.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Algorithm: Divide‐&‐Conquer DP on the bit‐trie of [0..m].
  We compute dp_u[k] = max sum picking k leaves from subtree u,
  matching them to A[1..k], accounting for each '1'‐bit edge via prefix sums.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;
const ll NEG_INF = (ll)(-9e18);

int n;
ll m;
vector<ll> A, P;  // A[1..n], P prefix sums

// dfs(bitPos, prefixLess) builds DP for subtree of all x whose bitwise prefix
// so far is either strictly less than m (prefixLess=true) or still matches m (false).
// Returns dp vector where dp[k] = max sum matching k picks to this subtree.
vector<ll> dfs(int bitPos, bool prefixLess) {
    // If we've gone below bit 0, that's a leaf: exactly one number.
    if (bitPos < 0) {
        vector<ll> dp(2, NEG_INF);
        // picking 0 leaves => sum=0; picking 1 leaf => sum=0 (bit contributions come above)
        dp[0] = 0;
        dp[1] = 0;
        return dp;
    }
    int mb = ((m >> bitPos) & 1);
    vector<ll> dpL, dpR;
    // Build left child?
    if (prefixLess || mb == 1 || mb == 0) {
        // left child always exists if either prefixLess or mb>=0
        bool nl = prefixLess || (mb == 1 ? true : false);
        dpL = dfs(bitPos - 1, nl);
    }
    // Build right child?
    if (prefixLess || mb == 1) {
        // prefixLess => full subtree; or mb==1 => we can take bit=1 branch matching m
        bool nr = prefixLess; 
        // if prefixLess==false and mb==1, then bit=1 matches m, so nr=false
        if (!prefixLess && mb == 1) nr = false;
        dpR = dfs(bitPos - 1, nr);
    }
    // If only left child:
    if (dpR.empty()) {
        // cannot go right, so dp = dpL
        if ((int)dpL.size() > n+1) dpL.resize(n+1);
        return dpL;
    }
    // If only right child (shouldn't happen in valid m-tree for [0..m])
    if (dpL.empty()) {
        if ((int)dpR.size() > n+1) dpR.resize(n+1);
        return dpR;
    }
    // Both children exist -> merge
    int szL = (int)dpL.size() - 1;
    int szR = (int)dpR.size() - 1;
    int tot = min(n, szL + szR);
    vector<ll> dp(tot + 1, NEG_INF);
    // Convolution with the +1‐bit cost for right picks:
    // dp[k] = max_{i+j=k} dpL[i] + dpR[j] + (P[i+j] - P[i])
    for (int i = 0; i <= szL; i++) if (dpL[i] > NEG_INF/2) {
        for (int j = 0; j <= szR && i + j <= tot; j++) if (dpR[j] > NEG_INF/2) {
            ll val = dpL[i] + dpR[j] + (P[i+j] - P[i]);
            dp[i+j] = max(dp[i+j], val);
        }
    }
    return dp;
}

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    cin >> n >> m;
    A.resize(n+1);
    P.assign(n+1, 0);
    for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
        cin >> A[i];
        P[i] = P[i-1] + A[i];
    }
    // Kick off DFS from the top bit of m
    int topBit = 0;
    for (int b = 60; b >= 0; b--) {
        if ((m >> b) & 1LL) {
            topBit = b;
            break;
        }
    }
    vector<ll> dpRoot = dfs(topBit, false);
    // dpRoot[k] is valid up to k <= n; answer is dpRoot[n]
    cout << dpRoot[n] << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

Explanation of key steps:
- We traverse bits from the most‐significant (topBit) down to 0, building an implicit trie of all x∈[0..m].
- At each node we maintain a DP array `dp_u[k]`: best total for selecting k leaves under this node to match `A[1..k]`.
- A right child choice at bitPos adds +1 to popcount for that bit, so those j picks incur an extra `sum A[...]`, handled via prefix sums `P`.
- Merging two child arrays is an O(n²) convolution; we cap sizes to ≤n to stay efficient.
- Finally, `dpRoot[n]` holds the maximum possible reward.

[Problem Analysis]

1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We must choose an strictly increasing sequence \(0 \le b_1 < b_2 < \cdots < b_n \le m\) to maximize  
     \[
       \sum_{i=1}^n \bigl(\mathrm{popcount}(b_i)\bigr)\times a_i.
     \]  
   - This is a “pick an increasing subsequence from a specially‐constructed set to maximize weighted sum of popcounts.”  We solve it by dynamic programming over a small candidate set.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - **Key Observation**:  Although \(b_i\) can be any integer up to \(10^{18}\), optimal choices occur only at certain “boundary” values where popcount tends to jump:  
     - 0,  
     - all powers of two \(2^k\),  
     - \(m\) itself,  
     - and for each 1‐bit in \(m\), the number formed by turning that bit off and setting all lower bits to 1.  
   - Collect these into a candidate array \(S\), sort and dedupe.  Its size is \(O(\log m)\).  
   - Let \(\mathrm{pc}[j]=\mathrm{popcount}(S[j])\).  We do a DP where  
     \[
       \mathrm{dp}[i][j]
       = \max_{k<j} \Bigl(\mathrm{dp}[i-1][k]\Bigr)
         + \mathrm{pc}[j]\times a_i.
     \]  
     We roll this to 1D: keep prefix‐maximums to speed transition to \(O(1)\) each.  
   - Finally the answer is \(\max_j \mathrm{dp}[n][j]\).

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Let \(M=|S|=O(\log m)\approx 60\).  
   - Time: \(O(n\times M)\) per DP layer to build prefix‐max plus \(O(M)\) updates ⇒ total \(O(n\,M)\approx 200\times60\).  
   - Space: \(O(M)\) for DP arrays.  
   - This is well within contest limits.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - All \(a_i\) negative ⇒ DP will pick the smallest popcounts first (often \(b_i=0\) or small powers of two).  
   - Ensure 64–bit arithmetic (use `long long`).  
   - Be careful to include \(0\) and handle the first row of DP (no previous element).

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Algorithm: DP over candidate set S of "boundary" numbers
  Key Techniques: 
    1) Generate S = {0, powers of two, m, m with one 1-bit turned off+lows set}
    2) Compute popcounts
    3) DP[i][j] = best for first i picks ending at S[j], use prefix‐max for O(1) transitions
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;
const ll INF = (ll)4e18;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(NULL);

    int n;
    ll m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<ll> a(n);
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        cin >> a[i];
    }

    // 1) Build candidate set S
    vector<ll> S;
    S.push_back(0);
    // powers of two
    for(int b = 0; b < 63; b++){
        ll x = (1ULL << b);
        if(x <= m) S.push_back(x);
        else break;
    }
    // m itself
    S.push_back(m);
    // For each 1-bit in m, clear it and set all lower bits to 1
    for(int b = 0; b < 63; b++){
        if( (m >> b) & 1 ){
            ll x = m;
            x &= ~(1ULL << b);           // clear bit b
            ll lowerMask = (1ULL << b) - 1;
            x |= lowerMask;              // set all bits < b
            S.push_back(x);
        }
    }
    sort(S.begin(), S.end());
    S.erase(unique(S.begin(), S.end()), S.end());

    int M = S.size();
    // 2) Precompute popcounts
    vector<int> pc(M);
    for(int i = 0; i < M; i++){
        pc[i] = __builtin_popcountll(S[i]);
    }

    // 3) DP arrays: dp_prev = dp for i-1, dp_cur for i
    vector<ll> dp_prev(M, -INF), dp_cur(M, -INF);

    // Build DP layer by layer
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
        // Compute prefix maxima of dp_prev
        vector<ll> prefMax(M, -INF);
        prefMax[0] = dp_prev[0];
        for(int j = 1; j < M; j++){
            prefMax[j] = max(prefMax[j-1], dp_prev[j]);
        }
        // Fill dp_cur
        for(int j = 0; j < M; j++){
            // If it's the first pick, we have no prior constraint
            if(i == 0){
                dp_cur[j] = (ll)pc[j] * a[i];
            } else {
                // we need k < j
                if(j > 0 && prefMax[j-1] > -INF/2){
                    dp_cur[j] = prefMax[j-1] + (ll)pc[j] * a[i];
                } else {
                    dp_cur[j] = -INF;
                }
            }
        }
        // swap for next iteration
        dp_prev.swap(dp_cur);
    }

    // 4) Answer is max over dp_prev[j]
    ll ans = *max_element(dp_prev.begin(), dp_prev.end());
    cout << ans << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation of Key Steps**  
- We only need \(O(\log m)\) “interesting” candidate values, since popcount changes only at these boundaries.  
- The DP enforces strictly increasing by only allowing transitions from index \(k<j\).  
- For speed, we keep a running prefix maximum of the previous DP row, so each new state is built in \(O(1)\).
